      "type": "thought",
      "text": "Perfect! Now I have the full CONTEXT.md and PHILOSOPHY.md from the Frappe UI library. This gives me the design philosophy and implementation principles for this UI library. Let me analyze what I've learned and how it applies to the user's request.\n\nKey insights from Frappe UI:\n\n1. **Component Vocabulary:**\n   - atom: primitive components that don't compose other public components\n   - molecule: composes atoms into higher-level controls\n   - Shared vocabulary for slot names, props, behaviors\n\n2. **State management:**\n   - `open` for overlay visibility\n   - `modelValue` for primary value\n   - `dismissible` for outside-click/Esc behavior\n\n3. **Design rules:**\n   - P1: Name behaviors, not interactions\n   - P2: Prefer v-model for two-way state\n   - P3: Prefer primitive prop types\n   - P4: Two color axes only (variant + theme)\n   - P5: Shared labeling contract for forms\n   - P6: Shared slot vocabulary\n   - P7: Slot props expose component state\n   - P8: Split components instead of overloading\n   - P9: Imperative APIs optimize for call-site boilerplate\n   - P10: Customize via slots and data-* attributes, never class-name props\n   - P11: Icon customization is uniform\n   - P12: Accessibility is non-negotiable\n   - P13: Deprecate, don't remove\n   - P14: Internals carry no promise\n\n4. **Implementation approach:**\n   - Use `defineModel` for reactive state\n   - Use `data-slot` and `data-state` for styling\n   - Follow semantic Tailwind tokens\n   - Use variant + theme color axes\n   - No semantic axes like intent/severity/appearance\n\nNow, for the user's store.ts implementation, I need to consider:\n\n\nI'll transform the store.ts implementation to align with Frappe UI's design principles. The new approach will leverage reactive state management, ensuring clean state handling and customization. I'll focus on creating intuitive components that can easily adapt to various scenarios while maintaining a consistent, predictable interface.",
